# get_next_line
 
## Description
 
`get_next_line` is a C function that reads a single line at a time from a file descriptor. Repeated calls to the function allow reading a file line by line until EOF. It works both with regular files and with standard input.
 
The function signature is:
```c
char *get_next_line(int fd);
```
It returns the line that was read (including the terminating `\n`), or `NULL` when there is nothing left to read or an error occurs.
 
## Instructions
 
Include `get_next_line.h` in your project and compile the three source files together:
 
```bash
cc -Wall -Wextra -Werror -D BUFFER_SIZE=42 get_next_line.c get_next_line_utils.c your_main.c
```
 
The `BUFFER_SIZE` macro controls how many bytes are read from the file descriptor at each `read()` call. It can be set at compile time with `-D BUFFER_SIZE=n`. If not specified, it defaults to `42`.
 
## Algorithm
 
The function uses a `static` local variable (`stash`) that persists between calls. This is the core of the implementation.
 
On each call to `get_next_line`:
 
1. `read()` is called repeatedly, appending data to `stash`, until a `\n` is found in `stash` or EOF is reached.
2. Once a `\n` is found, everything up to and including it is extracted and returned as the current line.
3. Whatever remains in `stash` after the `\n` is kept there for the next call, so no data is lost and no unnecessary `read()` calls are made.
This approach was chosen because it is straightforward, avoids reading the whole file at once, and handles any `BUFFER_SIZE` value correctly — including edge cases like `1` or very large values. The static variable is the only state that needs to survive between calls, without relying on global variables.
 
